#Read in individual data files
ndmi <- read.csv('hayman_ndmi.csv') %>%  
  rename(burned=2,unburned=3) %>%
  mutate(data='ndmi')


ndsi <- read.csv('hayman_ndsi.csv') %>% 
  rename(burned=2,unburned=3) %>%
  mutate(data='ndsi')

ndvi <- read.csv('hayman_ndvi.csv')%>% 
  rename(burned=2,unburned=3) %>%
  mutate(data='ndvi')

# Stack as a tidy dataset
full_long <- rbind(ndvi,ndmi,ndsi)%>%
  pivot_longer(.,cols=c('burned','unburned'),names_to="site") %>% #updated from gather(key='site',value='value',-DateTime,-data)
  filter(!is.na(value))

Questions to Address

Question 1

What is the correlation between NDVI and NDMI? - here I want you to convert the full_long dataset in to a wide dataset using the function spread and then make a plot that shows the correlation as a function of if the site was burned or not (x axis should be ndmi) You should exclude winter months and focus on summer months

Both sites displayed a positive relationship between NDMI and NDVI, implying that wetness is correlated with greenness. The burned site had a much wider spread of NDMI and NDVI values, which makes sense given the change in that area.

#change dataset from long to wide
full_wide <-full_long %>%  
  pivot_wider(.,id_cols=c('DateTime','site','value'),names_from = data) %>%  # updated from spread(key="data",value="value")
  filter(!is.na(ndvi)) %>% #remove NAs from each column
  filter(!is.na(ndsi)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(ndmi)) %>%
  mutate(month=month(DateTime), #convert date to month and year
         year=year(DateTime)) 

#Plot NDMI and NDVI
ggplot(full_wide%>%filter(month==c(5,6,7,8,9)),aes(ndmi,ndvi,color=site)) +
  geom_point()+ 
  geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE) +
  theme_bw() + 
  labs(title="Relationship Between NDMI and NDVI", subtitle="Comparing burned and unburned areas of the 2002 Hayman Fire")

Question 2

What is the correlation between average NDSI (normalized snow index) for January - April and average NDVI for June-August? In other words, does the previous years snow cover influence vegetation growth for the following summer?

There was not much of a relationship between winter NDSI and summer NDVI for both burned and unburned sites. Both sites showed similar values for NDSI, and the unburned having a much higher NDVI.

#Convert data to add in season field, and pivot wider to have one year row with summer ndvi and winter ndsi columns
full_long_season <- full_long %>%
  mutate(month=month(DateTime), #add in month and year from the date field
         year=year(DateTime)) %>%
  filter(month %in% c(1,2,3,4,6,7,8), #filter to only summer and winter months of interest, for only ndvi and ndsi
         data %in% c('ndvi','ndsi')) %>% 
  mutate(season=if_else(month %in% c(1,2,3,4),"winter","summer")) %>% #create new field for summer and winter, comprised of all months of interest
  group_by(season,year,site,data) %>% #group by season, year, burn status, and field type; summarize
  summarize(value=mean(value)) %>%
  filter(data=="ndvi" & season=="summer" | data=="ndsi" & season=="winter") %>% #select only for summer ndvi and winter ndsi
  .[c(1,2,3,5)] %>% #remove data field
  pivot_wider(.,id_cols=c('year', 'site', 'value'),names_from='season') #back to wide, summer/winter values each a column for each year; updated from  spread(key="season",value="value")

#Plot Winter NDSI and Summer NDVI
ggplot(full_long_season,aes(winter,summer,color=site)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE) +
  xlab("Winter (Jan-April) NDSI") + ylab("Summer (June-Aug) NDVI") + 
  labs(title="Relationship between Winter NDSI and Summer NDVI",subtitle="Comparing burned and unburned areas of the 2002 Hayman Fire")+ 
  theme_bw()

Question 3

How is the snow effect from question 2 different between pre- and post-burn and burned and unburned?

Winter NDSI still does not have much relationship to summer NDSI for either time point. Before the 2002 burn, both sites had fairly similar NDVI and NDSI values. After the burn, the burned area has much lower NDVI, as would be expected.

#add column 'burnstatus' to reflect pre or post 2002 fire
full_long_season_status <- full_long_season %>%
  mutate(burnstatus=if_else(year %in% c(1984:2002),"Before 2002 Burn","Post 2002 Burn"))

#Plot Winter NDSI and Summer NDVI, compring burned and unburned areas, faceted by time
ggplot(full_long_season_status,aes(winter,summer,color=site)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~burnstatus) +
  xlab("Winter (Jan-April) NDSI") + ylab("Summer (June-Aug) NDVI") + labs(title="Relationship between Winter NDSI and Summer NDVI",subtitle="Comparing burned and unburned areas before and after the 2002 Hayman Fire") + theme_bw()

Question 4

What month is the greenest month on average?

The greenest month on average is August for the burned area and September for the unburned area.

#Filter long data to contain just ndvi, arranged by month
full_long_month <- full_long %>%
  mutate(month=month(DateTime),
         year=year(DateTime)) %>%
  filter(data=='ndvi') %>%
  group_by(month,site) %>%
  summarize(value=mean(value))

#Plot NDVI over time
ggplot(full_long_month,aes(as.factor(month),value,fill=site)) +
  geom_col(position="dodge") + xlab("Month") + ylab("NDVI")+ labs(title="Seasonal NDVI in Burned and Unburned Areas of the 2002 Hayman Fire")+theme_bw()

Question 5

The snowiest month is January for the burned site and February for the unburned site.
